<section class="card">
  <h2>Common Mistakes When Measuring Soil Temperature</h2>

  <h3>Checking Only the Surface</h3>

  <p>
    The top layer of soil warms quickly in sun, but roots and seeds are usually working deeper down. Measure at planting depth, not just at the surface.
  </p>

  <h3>Relying on One Reading</h3>

  <p>
    Soil temperature shifts with weather. A single reading can be misleading, especially in spring. Check over a few days and look for a pattern.
  </p>

  <h3>Planting at the Bare Minimum</h3>

  <p>
    Minimum temperatures usually mean a crop can survive, not thrive. In short seasons, waiting for slightly better conditions often gives stronger early growth and less lost time.
  </p>

  <h3>Ignoring Wet Soil</h3>

  <p>
    Cold, saturated soil often behaves differently from moderately moist soil. Even when the thermometer looks acceptable, wet ground can still slow establishment.
  </p>

  <h3>Letting Air Temperature Fool You</h3>

  <p>
    A warm afternoon does not guarantee warm soil. Spring air often turns favorable before the root zone catches up.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The goal is not just a warm reading. The goal is steady conditions that support good establishment.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>What soil temperature is too cold for tomatoes?</summary>
    <p>
      Tomatoes struggle below 55°F (13°C) soil temperature.
      While they may survive brief exposure, root growth slows significantly.
      For steady establishment, aim for 60–65°F soil.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Is 50°F soil warm enough to plant?</summary>
    <p>
      For cool-season crops like lettuce or peas, yes.
      For warm-season crops such as tomatoes and peppers, 50°F is generally too cold for strong early growth.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Can I use a meat thermometer to measure soil temperature?</summary>
    <p>
      A kitchen thermometer can provide a rough reading,
      but it may not be durable enough for repeated use in damp soil.
      A dedicated soil probe is more reliable and corrosion-resistant.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Do raised beds warm faster than in-ground beds?</summary>
    <p>
      Yes. Raised beds typically warm more quickly in spring,
      especially if they receive full sun.
      However, they also cool faster during cold snaps.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Does black plastic warm soil effectively?</summary>
    <p>
      Black plastic mulch can increase soil temperature by several degrees
      by absorbing sunlight.
      It is often used to warm soil before transplanting warm-season crops.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>How often should I measure soil temperature?</summary>
    <p>
      During early spring, checking every few days is sufficient.
      Focus on trends rather than single readings.
    </p>
  </details>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>A Simple Rule for Using a Soil Thermometer</h2>

  <p>
    A soil thermometer is most useful when you use it to confirm what the garden is doing, not when you treat one reading as the whole answer.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Check frost timing first.</strong> Make sure you are at least in a reasonable outdoor planting window.</li>
    <li><strong>Measure at the right depth.</strong> Shallow checks can make the soil seem warmer than it really is.</li>
    <li><strong>Look for a trend.</strong> A few stable readings matter more than one warm afternoon.</li>
    <li><strong>Aim for good conditions, not just survival.</strong> Warm-season crops especially do better when soil is comfortably warm, not barely acceptable.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    For most home gardens, that is enough. You do not need perfect precision. You need a clear picture of whether the bed is actually ready to support growth.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    Measure for clarity, not complexity.
  </p>
</section>

